"#### Unicourt Jurisdictional Highlights (2020-2024):\n**Duration and resolution:**\n- Kings County\u2019s average personal injury case duration is 42% longer than Los Angeles County (830 vs 583 days) and 44% longer than Bronx County (830 vs 576 days). \n- Los Angeles County has the shortest average time to resolution, 25% faster than Bronx County (507 vs 678 days) and 42% faster than Kings County (507 vs 881 days).\n- Bronx County and Los Angeles County have near-identical average durations (576 vs 583 days; within 1%), but Bronx County\u2019s time to resolution is 34% longer than Los Angeles County (678 vs 507 days).\n- The spread between the fastest and slowest resolution venues is substantial: Kings County\u2019s time to resolution is 74% longer than Los Angeles County (881 vs 507 days).\n- Across these venues, the overall ranking for speed to resolution is Los Angeles County (fastest), then Bronx County, then Kings County (slowest).\n\n**TAKEAWAY**: This tells us that venue matters significantly for litigation timelines. Kings County represents the highest tail risk, while Los Angeles County offers faster resolution and better predictability.\n\n**Motions to dismiss:**\n- Motion to dismiss success rates are dramatically higher in New York than in Los Angeles County: Bronx County is 429% higher than Los Angeles County (33.77% vs 6.39%) and Kings County is 407% higher than Los Angeles County (32.4% vs 6.39%).\n- Bronx County\u2019s motion to dismiss success rate is 4% higher than Kings County (33.77% vs 32.4%), indicating a slight edge for early dismissals in Bronx County compared to Kings County.\n- Kings County has 92% more motions to dismiss than Bronx County (1,240 vs 647) and 231% more than Los Angeles County (1,240 vs 375), pointing to heavier motion practice in Kings County.\n- Average time to dismissal is longest in Kings County\u201463% longer than Bronx County (823 vs 504 days) and 44% longer than Los Angeles County (823 vs 570 days).\n- Los Angeles County\u2019s average time to dismissal is 13% longer than Bronx County (570 vs 504 days), underscoring that earlier exits by dismissal occur fastest in Bronx County.\n\n**TAKEAWAY**: Judicial philosophy differs by venue: New York courts (Bronx County and Kings County) grant motions to dismiss at far higher rates than Los Angeles County, but Kings County takes materially longer to reach dismissal than Bronx County.\n\n**No-trial durations:**\n- Personal injury cases that do not go to trial last 40% longer in Los Angeles County than Bronx County (70 vs 50 days).\n- Los Angeles County\u2019s no-trial duration is 27% longer than Kings County (70 vs 55 days).\n- Kings County\u2019s no-trial duration is 10% longer than Bronx County (55 vs 50 days).\n- Ranking on no-trial speed is Bronx County (fastest), then Kings County, then Los Angeles County (slowest).\n\n**TAKEAWAY**: Even without trial, Los Angeles County\u2019s personal injury cases stay open longer than in New York counties, while Bronx County offers the quickest no-trial path.\n\n**Summary judgment and closure:**\n- Summary judgment grant rates are highest in Los Angeles County, 14% higher than Kings County (73.56% vs 64.86%) and 121% higher than Bronx County (73.56% vs 33.33%).\n- Kings County is 95% higher than Bronx County on summary judgment success (64.86% vs 33.33%), reinforcing a stronger SJ posture than Bronx County.\n- Docket closure rates (closed/total PI caseload) are highest in Kings County at 33.2%, which is 27% higher than Bronx County (26.1%) and 13% higher than Los Angeles County (29.3%).\n- Los Angeles County\u2019s closure rate is 12% higher than Bronx County (29.3% vs 26.1%), despite slower no-trial timelines.\n\n**TAKEAWAY**: Summary judgment is most favorable in Los Angeles County, while Kings County closes a larger share of its docket; Bronx County trails both on SJ outcomes and overall closure rate.\n\n#### Coaction\u2019s Cases Jurisdictional Highlights (2020-2024):\n**Duration and resolution:**\n- Kings County\u2019s average personal injury duration is 41% longer than Bronx County (867 vs 615 days) and 20% longer than Los Angeles County (867 vs 723 days).\n- Bronx County has the fastest time to resolution among Coaction\u2019s venues\u20142.5% faster than Los Angeles County (682 vs 699 days) and 26% faster than Kings County (682 vs 857 days).\n- The gap between the slowest and fastest Coaction resolution venues is sizable: Kings County\u2019s time to resolution is 26% longer than Bronx County (857 vs 682 days).\n- Los Angeles County resolves Coaction personal injury matters 22% faster than Kings County (699 vs 857 days) on average resolution time.\n- Ranking on Coaction resolution speed: Bronx County (fastest), then Los Angeles County, then Kings County (slowest).\n\n**TAKEAWAY**: This tells us that venue matters significantly for Coaction\u2019s timelines. Kings County poses the longest durations and slowest resolutions, whereas Bronx County provides the quickest cycle for Coaction\u2019s personal injury cases.\n\n**Dismissals and no-trial timelines:**\n- Coaction\u2019s average time to dismissal is 92% longer in Kings County than Bronx County (796 vs 414 days).\n- For cases not proceeding to trial, Bronx County runs 13% longer than Kings County (54 vs 48 days).\n- Coaction\u2019s motions to dismiss were filed almost entirely in New York: 80% in Kings County (4 of 5) and 20% in Bronx County (1 of 5), with none in Los Angeles County.\n- With no Coaction motions to dismiss recorded in Los Angeles County, New York venues account for 100% of Coaction\u2019s personal injury dismissal motion activity across these jurisdictions.\n- Among these venues, Kings County shows more frequent use of dismissal motions than Bronx County (4x more filings), indicating heavier early-motion activity in Kings County for Coaction.\n\n**TAKEAWAY**: Coaction\u2019s dismissals arrive much faster in Bronx County than Kings County, and its dismissal motion practice is concentrated in New York, not Los Angeles County.\n\n**Volume and case closure:**\n- Coaction resolved far more personal injury cases in Kings County than Bronx County (32 vs 27; 19% higher), and both vastly exceed Los Angeles County (1 case).\n- Kings County accounts for 53% of Coaction\u2019s resolved personal injury cases across the three venues (32 of 60), with Bronx County at 45% (27 of 60) and Los Angeles County at 2% (1 of 60).\n- The New York venues collectively represent 98% of Coaction\u2019s resolved personal injury matters across these jurisdictions, underscoring where the caseload is concentrated.\n\n**TAKEAWAY**: Coaction\u2019s personal injury footprint (and thus operational impact) is overwhelmingly in New York courts, with Kings County leading resolved volume and Los Angeles County playing a minimal role."